    <section class="stroke-mechanics">
      <h2>The Science of the Stroke</h2>
      <p>Contrary to popular belief, paddling isn't about pulling water behind you. The most efficient stroke uses the entire arm as a lever, with the hand acting as a hydrofoil. Think of your arm like a wingâ€”it needs to generate lift, not just drag.</p>
      
      <p>The key is to maintain a high elbow position throughout the stroke. This isn't just about formâ€”it's about physics. When your elbow stays high, you create a longer lever arm, which means more power with less effort. Your hand should enter the water at a 45-degree angle, not straight down.</p>
      
