    <section class="common-pitfalls">
      <h2>What Most Surfers Get Wrong</h2>
      <p>The biggest mistake is treating paddling like swimming. Swimming is about moving your body through the water, but paddling is about moving your board through the water. These are completely different skills.</p>
      
      <p>Another common error is paddling too fast. Most surfers think they need to paddle as hard as possible, but this burns energy and creates tension. The goal is to find a sustainable rhythm that you can maintain for hours. If you're breathing hard after paddling out, you're going too fast.</p>
      
      <p>Finally, don't neglect your legs. While you shouldn't kick to paddle, your legs are crucial for balance and board control. Keep them relaxed but engaged, ready to help with turns and positioning.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="practice-methodology">
      <h2>How to Practice</h2>
      <p>Practice paddling like you practice surfingâ€”with intention and focus. Don't just paddle aimlessly. Set goals: paddle to a specific point, maintain a certain pace, or work on a specific technique.</p>
      
      <p>Start with short sessions focused on technique. Paddle for 10 minutes focusing only on your stroke mechanics. Then paddle for 10 minutes focusing only on your breathing. Break it down into manageable pieces.</p>
      
      <p>Film yourself paddling. What you feel and what you're actually doing are often different. Watch your stroke, your body position, and your breathing. You'll be surprised at what you discover.</p>
      
